    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.15.45"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">45</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        324 Prospect
                        Long Beach,Cal
                        June 10 1932
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr.John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi>Neihardt,</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson,Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>For years I have been lecturing before colleges anduniversities<sic>and universities</sic> on modern poetry. Having published seven books of execrable verse (all of which, thank God, is out of print), I knew good poetry when I meet iy<sic>it</sic>,--which makes me glad mine has passed into innocuous desuetude.</p>
                
                <p>In these lectures I try to place you as our great epic poet on the pioneer days. I think I have been somewhat successful in this.</p>
                
                <p>Will you do me a favor by signing the enclosed poem for me to frame and place in my own Po<del/><add>e</add>ts' <del/><add>C</add>orner, along with similarly signed verses by Chesteton<sic>Chesterton</sic>, Barrie, Housman, Robinson, Millay, Sandburg,Drinkwater, and other of the immortals. Also, will you sign the fly-leaf from "Song of High<sic>Hugh</sic> Glass" enclosed.</p>
                
                <p>I belong to the California Group of Missouri Writers' Guilders, which is quite active. You may look me up in Who's Who, to place me. I enclose my folder for the same purpose.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sinvcerely<sic>Sincerely</sic>,</salute>
               
                    <signed>M L <unclear>Merthe</unclear></signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
